## Nadzu-back (Rust Backend)

API server built with `axum`, structured in modules for routes, controllers, models, middleware, and custom extractors.

### Current Scope

- ❌ PostgreSQL disabled for now
- ❌ Redis disabled for now

### Request/Response Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart TD
		A[Client] --> B[TCP Listener tokio::net::TcpListener]
		B --> C[axum::serve]
		C --> D[Router from routes::create_router]

		D --> E[Rate Limiter Layer]
		E --> F[CORS Layer]
		F --> G[Compression Layer]
		G --> H[Trace Layer]

		H --> I{Route Match}
		I -->|GET /| J[root_controller::root_handler]
		I -->|GET /health| K[health_controller::check_health]
		I -->|POST /validate-user| L[validation_controller::validate_user]
		I -->|POST /api/v1/ytdlp/| Y[ytdlp_controller::create_download_job]
		I -->|No Match| M[error_controller::not_found_handler]

		L --> N[ValidatedJson extractor]
		N --> O[validator::Validate]
		O -->|ok| P[ValidatedUserResponse]
		O -->|error| Q[422 JSON error payload]
```

### How the Code Works

#### 1) Program Entry

- `src/main.rs` declares modules and runs `app::run()` inside `#[tokio::main]`.
- `tokio` provides async runtime so handlers and networking are non-blocking.

#### 2) App Boot (`src/app.rs`)

Boot sequence:

1. Load environment variables with `dotenvy::dotenv()`.
2. Initialize tracing/logging with `tracing_subscriber`.
3. Build `AppConfig` from env (`src/config.rs`).
4. Create `AppState` containing shared config.
5. Build middleware layers:
	 - Rate limiter (`src/middleware/rate_limit.rs`)
	 - CORS (`src/middleware/cors.rs`)
	 - Compression (`tower_http::compression`)
	 - Request tracing (`tower_http::trace`)
6. Build router from `src/routes/mod.rs`.
7. Bind TCP listener and start server.
8. Wait for Ctrl+C graceful shutdown.

#### 3) Routing (`src/routes/*`)

- `/` -> `root_handler`
- `/health` -> `check_health`
- `/validate-user` -> `validate_user` (POST)
- `/api/v1/ytdlp/` -> enqueue a yt-dlp job (POST)
- `/api/v1/ytdlp/jobs` -> list jobs (GET)
- `/api/v1/ytdlp/jobs/{id}` -> get job by id (GET)
- fallback -> JSON 404 response

#### 4) Controllers (`src/controllers/*`)

- `root_controller`: simple text response proving server is alive.
- `health_controller`: returns typed JSON `{ status, version }`.
- `validation_controller`: accepts validated JSON, returns structured success payload.
- `error_controller`: catches unmatched paths and returns consistent JSON 404.

#### 5) Validation Pipeline (`src/extractors/validated_json.rs`)

`ValidatedJson<T>` is a custom extractor:

1. Parse JSON body into `T`.
2. Run `validator::Validate` rules from your model.
3. If parsing fails -> `400 Bad Request` with details.
4. If validation fails -> `422 Unprocessable Entity` with field-level errors.
5. If valid -> handler receives strongly-typed payload.

This avoids manual validation logic inside controllers.

#### 6) Data Models (`src/models/*`)

- `ValidateUserRequest` defines request schema and validation constraints.
- `ValidatedUserResponse` and `UserData` define output shape.
- `Health` defines health endpoint output.

Because structs derive `Serialize`/`Deserialize`, Axum + Serde convert JSON automatically.

#### 7) Error Type (`src/error.rs`)

- `AppError` wraps internal errors with `anyhow::Error`.
- Implements `IntoResponse`, so handlers can return it directly.
- Internal details are logged; client receives generic `500 Internal Server Error`.

### Environment Variables

Optional/basic:

- `APP_NAME` (default: `nadzu_api`)
- `APP_ENV` (default: `production`)
- `APP_HOST` (default: `127.0.0.1`)
- `APP_PORT` (default: `8080`)
- `ALLOWED_ORIGINS` (comma-separated, e.g. `http://localhost:3000` or `*`)
- `DOWNLOAD_DIR` (default: `downloads`)
- `YTDLP_PATH` (default: `yt-dlp`)
- `YTDLP_COOKIES_FILE` (optional absolute/relative path to `cookies.txt`)
- `YTDLP_OUTPUT_TEMPLATE` (default: `%(title)s.%(ext)s`)
- `YTDLP_EXTRACTOR_ARGS` (optional, forwarded to `yt-dlp --extractor-args`)
- `YTDLP_POT_PROVIDER_URL` (optional; if set, auto-builds extractor args for bgutil)
- `MAX_CONCURRENT_DOWNLOADS` (default: `3`)

### Run

```bash
cargo run
```

### Test Endpoints Quickly

```bash
curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/
curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/health
curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8080/validate-user \
	-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
	-d '{"name":"Alice","email":"alice@example.com","age":24}'

curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8080/api/v1/ytdlp/ \
	-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
	-d '{"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ","quality":"best","format":"mp4"}'
```

